	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64155719"><p><div class="quote"><p>There is no sonic boom in steady super sonic flight.</p></div><p>Unfortunately, that is not the case. Yes, there is a sonic boom when a plane is in steady supersonic flight. The previous commenter ("Latent Heat") had it correctly: the sonic boom is a cone-shaped shock-wave of sound trailing behind the airplane, with the apex at the airplane.
</p><p>(in fact, a "sonic boom" has two "boom" like noises, the compression shockwave and the expansion shockwave.).</p><p><div class="quote"><p> Unless you fly more or less exactly at the speed of sound. A super sonic airplane: You do not hear coming.</p></div><p>True. The shock wave trails behind the airplane</p><p><div class="quote"><p>You hear no boom when it goes over you.</p></div><p>True. The shock wave trails behind the airplane</p><p><div class="quote"><p>You hear the engine when it is far enough away.</p></div><p>Not just the engine noise (which is soft compared to the sonic boom) The shock wave ("sonic boom") hits you after the airplane has passed.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64155719">
